title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 61-3 .22LR
postcontent: Up for sale I have a very nice S&W Model 61-3. This is known as the "Escort", why it was called that I'll leave to you to decide. Basically this was a very revolutionary design and change up for Smith as they were experimenting with semi autos. This particular model was designed with concealed carry in mind. Initially thought of for women but many men became interested in it as a potential back up gun. The pistol was designed to compete with the Colt Junior, and the idea was that it would be cheaper to shoot (.22lr) and maintain similar ballistics. The original model 61 suffered some reliability problems but by the last variation, 61-3, they were able to eliminate those issues. What that translates to is that there were not a lot of Model 61's produced period. They were only made for 3 years basically, this one being a 1973. This is the blued version, the finish is very nice with a little thinning occurring on the edges of the gun. The pistol has bakelite or plastic grip panels. They are in very good shape as well. There appears to be 2 minor scuffs on the left panel. The right is very nice. The pistol comes with one original magazine. The mags hold 5 rounds for these guns. From what I have read if you are planning to shoot the gun, just use high velocity ammo (mini mags, stingers, etc) and it should be flawless. These guns with the box go for about $500-600 because many Smith and Wesson collectors are grabbing them up. This is a great opportunity to get this one for a reasonable price as they are just beginning to rise! I test fired the pistol using cci mini mags and cci blazer standard velocity. i shot 50 rounds of each through the pistol with zero failures. pistol ran through everything without a hiccup.
